19–":"about 1119–Deceased","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1165–1214":"1165–1214","1119–Female":"1119–Deceased","1214":"1214","about 1119":"about 1119","1165":"1165","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","about 1165":"about 1165","1119":"1119","Hollingbourn, Kent, England":"Hollingbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fossard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fozard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fozard","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from the Old French personal name  <i>Fossard</i>."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Baroness Joan de Fossard was born about 1119, in Hollingbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Baron Robert de Turnham."},"et":{"about 1119–":"umbes 1119–Surnud","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1165–1214":"1165–1214","1119–Female":"1119–Surnud","1214":"1214","about 1119":"umbes 1119","1165":"1165","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","about 1165":"umbes 1165","1119":"1119","Hollingbourn, Kent, England":"Hollingbourne, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1119–":"noin 1119–Kuollut","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1165–1214":"1165–1214","1119–Female":"1119–Kuollut","1214":"1214","about 1119":"noin 1119","1165":"1165","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","about 1165":"noin 1165","1119":"1119","Hollingbourn, Kent, England":"Hollingbourne, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1119–":"environ 1119–Décédée","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1165–1214":"1165–1214","1119–Female":"1119–Décédée","1214":"1214","about 1119":"environ 1119","1165":"1165","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","about 1165":"environ 1165","1119":"1119","Hollingbourn, Kent, England":"Hollingbourne, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Baroness Joan de Fossard est née environ 1119, à Hollingbourne, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Baron Robert de Turnham."},"de":{"about 1119–":"um 1119–Verstorben","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1165–1214":"1165–1